Date: 0/0/1924
Source: NZ Journal of Science & Technology
Author:
Vol / Page: 6/262 Fig. 7
Edition:
Quote: Smooth-hound, <i>Mustelus antarcticus</i>. ...This shark was known to the Maoris as `koinga.' <i>Ibid.</i> 263 <i>Mustelus antarcticus</i>. Synonyms: <i>Galeus antarcticus</i> and <i>Galeorhinus antarcticus</i>. The smooth-hound, or gummy (<i>Mustelus antarcticus</i>) ... is one of the small sharks commonly taken by trawlers around new Zealand, and popularly termed `dogfish.' The family is distinguished by the blunt pavement-like teeth - hence the popular name `gummy,' in use in Australia, where the species is also common. (Phillipps)
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1927
